(Mocquard, 1897)
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C5DE9CD3FFF22703659BFA5E82A6967D" pageId="37" pageNumber="338" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="8D7BCF58FFF22703659BFA5E82A6967D" blockId="37.[151,1436,1483,1618]" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">
<taxonomicName id="4AC4B4DBFFF22703659BFA5E832D95C9" authority="Mocquard, 1897" authorityName="Mocquard" authorityYear="1897" box="[151,565,1483,1509]" class="Amphibia" family="Hyperoliidae" genus="Rappia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="338" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tuberculata">
<emphasis id="BFB0134AFFF22703659BFA5E806895C9" box="[151,368,1483,1509]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">Rappia tuberculata</emphasis>
Mocquard, 1897
</taxonomicName>
. MNHNP 96.570 “Lambaréné”, 
<collectingCountry id="F5D38FC8FFF2270366A4FA5982EB95C9" box="[936,1011,1483,1509]" name="Gabon" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">Gabon</collectingCountry>
(
<tableCitation id="C046FAE3FFF22703610FFA59854295C9" box="[1027,1114,1483,1509]" captionStart="TABLE 3" captionStartId="43.[151,239,151,175]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="TABLE 3. Codes, localities and co-ordinates for the types and taxa now regarded as junior synonyms of the Hyperolius species, used in figs. 4–10." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/D9BB9FD0FFFC270D659BFF0580AE90FF" pageId="37" pageNumber="338" tableUuid="D9BB9FD0FFFC270D659BFF0580AE90FF">Table 3</tableCitation>
). Back and exposed parts of limbs light reddish-brown back with many fine tubercles. A brown stripe is sometimes present from the eye to the snout tip. Another mark of the same colour reaches the eye from the top of the head, while another starts at the lower edge of the eye, running obliquely to the angle of the jaw.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C5DE9CD3FFF22703659BF9ED83159795" pageId="37" pageNumber="338" type="description">
<paragraph id="8D7BCF58FFF22703659BF9ED806E9729" blockId="37.[151,1436,1663,1978]" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">
This clade consists of 30 sequences from 
<collectingCountry id="F5D38FC8FFF227036779F9ED83DA96B5" box="[629,706,1663,1689]" name="Gabon" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">Gabon</collectingCountry>
, Bioko Island (
<collectingCountry id="F5D38FC8FFF22703667DF9ED855B96B6" box="[881,1091,1663,1690]" name="Equatorial Guinea" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">Equatorial Guinea</collectingCountry>
) and 
<collectingCountry id="F5D38FC8FFF227036188F9ED85E196B5" box="[1156,1273,1663,1689]" name="Cameroon" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">Cameroon</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="15FFD3DDFFF227036006F9ED847D96B5" box="[1290,1381,1663,1689]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="38.[151,250,638,662]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,615]" captionTargetId="figure-33@38.[151,1436,181,615]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 9. Localities of sequences (black circles), type localities (stars) and location of junior synonyms of Hyperolius bangwae (A), H. tuberculatus (B), and H. glandicolor (C). Locality codes are explained in Table 3." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6538298" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6538298/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">Fig. 9B</figureCitation>
). All sequences were reported in GenBank as 
<taxonomicName id="4AC4B4DBFFF22703676BF931826E9691" baseAuthorityName="Mocquard" baseAuthorityYear="1897" box="[615,886,1699,1725]" class="Amphibia" family="Hyperoliidae" genus="Hyperolius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="338" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tuberculatus">
<emphasis id="BFB0134AFFF22703676BF931826E9691" box="[615,886,1699,1725]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">Hyperolius tuberculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The sequence reported in 
<bibRefCitation id="E955B2A9FFF2270361A0F93184649691" author="Veith" box="[1196,1404,1699,1726]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Veith" pageId="37" pageNumber="338" pagination="388 - 393" refId="ref35016" refString="Veith, M., Kosuch, J., Rodel, M. - O., Hillers, A., Schmitz, A., Burger, M. &amp; Lotters, S. (2009) Multiple evolution of sexual dichromatism in African reed frogs. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 51, 388 - 393. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2008.12.022" type="journal article" year="2009">
Veith 
<emphasis id="BFB0134AFFF2270361E3F936843A9691" box="[1263,1314,1699,1725]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">et al</emphasis>
. (2009)
</bibRefCitation>
as 
<taxonomicName id="4AC4B4DBFFF22703659BF95580BD96CD" baseAuthorityName="Mocquard" baseAuthorityYear="1897" box="[151,421,1735,1761]" class="Amphibia" family="Hyperoliidae" genus="Hyperolius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="338" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tuberculatus">
<emphasis id="BFB0134AFFF22703659BF95580BD96CD" box="[151,421,1735,1761]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">Hyperolius tuberculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Complex A forms part of this species. The uncorrected 
<emphasis id="BFB0134AFFF22703611AF95A853596CD" box="[1046,1069,1736,1761]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">p-</emphasis>
distances from other clades were 2.1–6.2% (
<tableCitation id="C046FAE3FFF22703641DF97980719729" box="[273,361,1771,1797]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="20.[151,239,762,788]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="TABLE 2. Uncorrected minimum p-distances as percentages between the clades. GOE—Hyperolius goetzei, NOB—H. noblei, MAR—H. mariae, VIR—H. viridiflavus, GLA— H. glandicolor, MAG—H. marginatus, TUB—H. tuberculosa, BAN—H. bangwae, DIN—H. dintelmanni, MOR—H. marmoratus, NIT—H. nitidulus, SPA—H. spatzi, PAR—H. parallelus." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/D9BB9FD0FFC32732659BFD6880129370" pageId="37" pageNumber="338" tableUuid="D9BB9FD0FFC32732659BFD6880129370">Table 2</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8D7BCF58FFF22703659BF89D84519705" blockId="37.[151,1436,1663,1978]" box="[151,1353,1807,1834]" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">
The pattern element in the description of the 
<typeStatus id="527F71FAFFF227036783F88283A79706" box="[655,703,1808,1834]" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">type</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="4AC4B4DBFFF2270367E9F882828A9705" baseAuthorityName="Mocquard" baseAuthorityYear="1897" box="[741,914,1807,1833]" class="Amphibia" family="Hyperoliidae" genus="Hyperolius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="338" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tuberculatus">
<emphasis id="BFB0134AFFF2270367E9F882828A9705" box="[741,914,1807,1833]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">H. tuberculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
consists of various stripes on the head.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8D7BCF58FFF2270365CBF8A183159795" blockId="37.[151,1436,1663,1978]" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">
The advertisement call (no vouchers) is a high-pitched long series of notes (
<bibRefCitation id="E955B2A9FFF227036114F8A185F99761" author="Bosch" box="[1048,1249,1843,1870]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Bosch" pageId="37" pageNumber="338" pagination="246 - 255" refId="ref29357" refString="Bosch, J., De la Riva, I. &amp; Marquez, R. (2000) Advertisement calls of seven species of hyperoliid frogs, from Equatorial Guinea. Amphibia-Reptilia, 21, 246 - 255." type="journal article" year="2000">
Bosch 
<emphasis id="BFB0134AFFF22703616BF8A685809761" box="[1127,1176,1843,1869]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">et al</emphasis>
. 2000
</bibRefCitation>
, from 
<collectingCountry id="F5D38FC8FFF227036025F8A184809761" box="[1321,1432,1843,1869]" name="Equatorial Guinea" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">Río Muni</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F5D38FC8FFF22703659BF8C58070975E" box="[151,360,1879,1906]" name="Equatorial Guinea" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">Equatorial Guinea</collectingCountry>
), with an emphasised frequency of 3228 Hz, and a mean note rate of 
<geoCoordinate id="E8F0A99FFFF22703617CF8C585A09749" box="[1136,1208,1879,1906]" degrees="11.6" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="37" pageNumber="338" precision="5555" value="-11.6">
11.6 
<superScript id="7AB16210FFF2270361ABF8CA85A09749" attach="left" box="[1191,1208,1879,1906]" fontSize="6" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">s-</superScript>
</geoCoordinate>
1. A call from Adjap, 
<collectingCountry id="F5D38FC8FFF22703659BF8E9801497B9" box="[151,268,1915,1941]" name="Cameroon" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">Cameroon</collectingCountry>
(no voucher) is a series of double pulsed notes with a note rate of 6 
<superScript id="7AB16210FFF227036100F8EE853C97A5" attach="left" box="[1036,1060,1915,1942]" fontSize="6" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">s-1</superScript>
, and an emphasised frequency of 3000 Hz (
<bibRefCitation id="E955B2A9FFF227036409F80D83199795" author="Amiet &amp; Goutte" box="[261,513,1951,1977]" firstAuthor="Amiet" pageId="37" pageNumber="338" refId="ref28611" refString="Amiet, J. - L. &amp; Goutte, S. (2017) Chants d'Amphibiens du Cameroun. J. - L. Amiet &amp; Editions Petit Genies, Nyons, 280 pp." type="book" year="2017">Amiet &amp; Goutte 2017</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
